text: I can't be the only person who thinks this looks horrible. Comedy is probably my favorite movie genre and even I can't see how anybody thinks this will be good. It's literally just one joke stretched out into two movies.  "Lol, it's funny because he's a teddy bear and teddy bears don't normally do things like that!"  Not to mention just the trailer itself already contains two jokes lifted straight from Family Guy. This is just a lazy moneygrab for stupid people who will watch anything and the Hollywood execs behind it will be laughing about it all the way to the bank.  I'm not trying to be a jerk. Honestly, I never judge people for anything. But this is one situation where I seriously just have no idea how people could fathom paying money for this movie. Oh well. Watch what you want, I guess. It's not like it affects me in any way. It's just depressing that shit like this is accepted as "funny" by so many people.

text: Did you know?: a group of linguists found that the English language was the best language in the world.   The Cornell-Bentley Research   A few years ago, a group of linguists carried out a research to find out the linguistic qualities of modern languages and the intellectual characterisitcs of their speakers. The research was based on a number of parameters (example:  economy of language, lexico grammatical simplicity and lexical richness). The study also included an inquiry into the psycholinguistic feeding produced by subjects from different parts of the world. The scientists concluded that the English language as spoken in the last two decades of the 20th century had outstanding qualities, standing out from the rest of the languages in the world. In addition, they reported that this language was necessarily the communication means of highly-evolved, highly-civilized human beings. According to the scientists, the evidence showed that the English language was beyond the expected standards, and that the speakers who originated this language had massive neuronal connections at the level of the cortex and a high rate of intercommunication between the cerebral hemispheres at the level of corpus callosum. On the other hand, languages like Spanish and Italian were below the linguistic standards -therefore they called them “low-level languages”- and their speakers showed weaker cerebral settings. After the results of this study were known, certain economic and political corporations strongly forbade the scientists from revealing either the details of the study or its results. Seemingly, the corporations fear that this study may cause socio-political distress in non-English-speaking countries, leading to an eventual fall in the exportation/importation flow of English-speaking countries. As a result, this research is not available in the Internet or any other place, representing a real breach of the right of free speech guaranteed by the American constitution. Because of this, a group of citizens concerned with this situation decided to launch a campaign against this breach of rights and are currently making this study known to the world.

text: Haha!  Seeing Sam presiding over the wedding reminded me of something that happened a long time ago....I played my (now ex-) fiancee the Wedding March from the _Flash Gordon_ soundtrack, and told her that I wanted that played at _our_ wedding.  She just smirked and chuckled and shook her head like she thought I was kidding.  I've never seen anybody run that fast from a church, let alone in a wedding dress, and dragging her daddy behind her!  After she was gone, I did what any sane man would've done--turned around, proposed to the Maid of Honor and married her on the spot (she was already mother to two of my kids, after all).  And there was much rejoicing.    Anyway, I'll bet my bottom dollar that's what happens in this movie--Ted and Tami-Lynn get married to the beautiful strains of Queen's rock-opera version of the Wedding March.

text: I saw this the other night and honestly was not impressed. The first movie was getting a lot of attention and was amazing because it was a whole new concept and everyone was attracted by the whole idea of a talking teddy bear, but the second one wasn't as exciting because we're already used to the whole concept (than again, some people aren't!). And also, way too much crude humor. Trust me, I do love crude humor, but there wasn't a single joke in this movie that I didn't feel embarrassed to sit in the theatre with my dad from. But overall, it did have some pretty good parts, and some pretty fucked up ones. If you prefer crude, inappropriate, adult humor, than I highly recommend this movie. If you enjoy appropriate, funny, family humor, don't even attempt to watch this movie.
